# Proposed Update — citation-audit.md

**Source:** SkillTest R3.B case-mixed-claims (no-network) + R6.B
case-real-crossref (with network).
**Status:** Draft only. Do not apply to
`/Users/mjm/MinionsOS/minions/roles/writer/skills/citation-audit.md`
until the user explicitly approves.

## What to add

The current `citation-audit.md` already enforces the three-layer check
(existence, metadata, context) and names canonical sources. Add the
following hard rules under the Procedure section.

### Add Rule: Never trust Crossref query.title rank-1 without sanity check

> **Crossref `query.title` rank-1 is polluted for famous papers.**
> Verify all three of:
> - **Year**: matches the year the paper was actually published.
> - **Container**: matches the expected journal / conference name.
> - **First author family name**: matches the canonical first author.
>
> If ANY check fails, fall back to direct DOI lookup (e.g.
> `10.18653/v1/N19-1423` for BERT) or to the venue's own bibliographic
> page. Do NOT accept rank-1 just because it's the top result.

Evidence: SkillTest R6.B case-real-crossref. Two of four famous-paper
queries returned non-canonical rank-1 records:
- Vaswani 2017 → `10.65215/r5bs2d54` → 2025 Shenzhen Medical Academy.
- Devlin 2019 BERT → `10.1080/10598650.2014.11510796` → 2014 Journal of
  Museum Education paper.

Without the sanity check, a Writer that "trusts the API" emits two
fabricated citations confidently. With the sanity check, the failure
is caught and the fallback (direct DOI lookup) succeeds.

### Add Rule: `[needs verification]` placeholder is the right output when blocked

> **When existence cannot be verified — no canonical source resolves,
> no DOI returns sanity-check-passing metadata — emit
> `[needs verification]` rather than fabricating.** This is a valid
> output. Author / next-pass reviewer fills it before submission.

Evidence: SkillTest R3.B (no-network). Both baseline and candidate
correctly used `[needs verification]` placeholders for all citations
when no network was available; the discipline transferred to the
network-enabled R6.B case where placeholders were used only when
sanity checks failed.

### Add Rule: Aggregator pages are not canonical

> **ResearchGate, Academia.edu, Semantic Scholar's surface page,
> Google Scholar's snippet, and similar aggregators are NOT canonical
> sources for verification.** Use:
> - DOI resolver (`https://doi.org/<DOI>`)
> - Publisher venue page (e.g. `nature.com/articles/<id>`)
> - arXiv (`arxiv.org/abs/<id>`) — for preprints only; check for the
>   accepted-version DOI separately
> - DBLP (`dblp.org/...`) — for CS conferences
> - ACL Anthology (`aclanthology.org/...`)
> - OpenReview (`openreview.net/forum?id=<id>`)

(Already in the current skill — kept for emphasis.)

### Add Rule: Watch for arXiv → conference version drift

> **arXiv v1 vs accepted-conference-version drift** can change the
> title, abstract, and even the year of a paper. When citing, prefer
> the accepted-version DOI. If only the arXiv version exists, mark
> the entry `arXiv preprint` explicitly.

Evidence: SkillTest R3.B. Baseline accepted titles from arXiv pages
even when the published version had a different title.

## What to leave unchanged

- The three-layer check (existence, metadata, context).
- The per-entry verdict format (`OK / DRIFT / MISSING / WRONG_CONTEXT`).
- The output structure (`CITATION_AUDIT.md` + `CITATION_AUDIT.json`).
- The procedure ordering (gate timing → extract pairs → existence →
  metadata → context → record verdicts).
- The pitfalls list.

## Why these are the right additions

R3.B + R6.B cross-validate the network-on / network-off failure modes:

| Round | Network | Failure mode | Skill action |
|---|---|---|---|
| R3.B | off | Cannot verify | `[needs verification]` placeholder |
| R6.B | on | Crossref rank-1 polluted | Sanity check (year + container + first author) → fallback to DOI lookup |

Without the R6.B rule, a network-enabled Writer can emit fabricated
citations at scale (R6.B baseline emitted two within a single 4-citation
batch). With the rule, the failure is caught.

The R3.B placeholder rule is already implicit in the current skill's
"unresolvable → MISSING" handling; this update makes the placeholder
the explicit allowed output rather than treating MISSING as a hard
failure that demands removal.

## Bucket upgrade

R3.B verdict was `Calibrates response`; R6.B verdict is **`Prevents real
failure`** (rank-1 trust without sanity check is a hard fabrication
path). For MinionsOS Writer in production with network access, this
update is load-bearing.
